her issues, but I never saw administrators make such faces every time they saw anyone but our older girl!  The public school policy was punishment, plain and simple.  If you did anything wrong you got cut from the field trip, the water day, the field day, the movie, anything the child saw as fun.  Christian schools are not all the same, but the one we liked had a policy that if you did wrong, we know you will try to do better.  Both our girls loved it.  They flourished.  The more troubled one did graduate from public school (returned to it for high school).  The younger one went back to public school in middle school, and is now in graduate school working on an MBA and has a full time job in Human Resources.  You have to do what is right for your child.  I couldn't change the system, so I had to do right by my daughter. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1129" language="en" documentId="2740" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Threedogmom" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:22PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="18" thumbsDown="0" origId="2740" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1129"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>